<P>

Subdivision methods recursively refine the control mesh 
(i.e.&nbsp;the input mesh) and generate points approximating 
the limit surface. 
Designed to work on the class <I><A HREF="../Polyhedron_ref/Class_Polyhedron_3.html#Cross_link_anchor_1110">Polyhedron_3</A></I>,
<I><A HREF="Class_Subdivision_method_3.html#Cross_link_anchor_1578">Subdivision_method_3</A></I> aims to be easy to use and to extend.
<I><A HREF="Class_Subdivision_method_3.html#Cross_link_anchor_1578">Subdivision_method_3</A></I> is not a class, but a namespace 
which consists of four popular subdivision methods and their refinement
hosts. Supported subdivision methods include Catmull-Clark, Loop, 
Doo-Sabin and <span class="math">&radic;<span style="text-decoration:overline">3</span></span> subdivisions. Their respective refinement 
hosts are PQQ, PTQ, DQQ and <span class="math">&radic;<span style="text-decoration:overline">3</span></span> refinements.
Variations of those methods can be easily 
extended by substituting the geometry computation of the refinement
host.
<P>

